7:33:35?\n\n### The `6f96e304` Message: The Outbox Retry of an Earlier Message\n\nThe \"Outbox retried 1 message\" Alice log at 17:33:45 (lines 28-29) is coincidental with the initial send of `3ec04fdf`. Looking at Alice log line 30 — \"Message delivered directly (Direct tier)\" — this is logged from `send_message_tiered_internal()` when `phase.is_direct()` (line 1188), meaning this is the INITIAL `send_text_tiered` call for `3ec04fdf` where Direct tier succeeded immediately.\n\nThe outbox retry of \"1 message\" at 17:33:45 is a DIFFERENT message — it is `6f96e304`. That earlier message was sent by Alice at ~17:33:35 (or earlier), initially failed Direct tier (LAN peer not yet verified), went into Urgent phase, and `outbox_tick` retried it at 17:33:45 via the legacy `attempt_delivery` → `BroadcastAll` path. Bob received `6f96e304` at 17:33:35 — that was either via a stable node (Bob was fetching from it) or the initial `submit_tiered` partially succeeded via a Quorum target that Bob's client was subscribed to.\n\nBut \"Message from LAN peer stored successfully\" means Bob's LAN HTTP server received it, not a stable-node fetch. So `6f96e304` reached Bob's LAN HTTP server at 17:33:35 from Alice's INITIAL `submit_tiered` where:\n- Direct tier tried Bob's LAN server → Bob stored it (17:33:35)\n- But Direct tier TIMED OUT on Alice's side (500ms default, Bob responded slower)\n- Alice records Direct tier failure → tries Quorum → also fails → Urgent phase, retry in 5s\n\nThen at 17:33:45 (10 seconds later), `outbox_tick` fires and calls `attempt_delivery(6f96e304)` → `submit_message` (BroadcastAll) → sends `6f96e304` to Bob's LAN HTTP server AGAIN. Bob's dedup check at line 300-321 in `http_server.rs` catches this and returns 200 with no \"stored successfully\" log — just a \"Duplicate message, already stored\" debug log.\n\nSimultaneously, Alice's TUI user presses Enter for the new message, creating `3ec04fdf` and calling `send_text_tiered`. Direct tier succeeds (Bob's LA