ler cannot determine whether identity verification is possible before probing.\n**Status:** Deviation\n\n---\n\n### [MAJOR] TXT Record Contains `port` Field Not in the Discovery Contract\n**Spec reference:** Plan, Discovery Contract\n**Finding:** The plan's Discovery Contract lists `v`, `rk`, `relay`, and `identity` as TXT keys. The implementation adds a `port` field not present in the contract. The ROADMAP.md v0.4 section mentions `port=<http_port>` in the older TXT description, but the detailed plan (which supersedes the roadmap) does not include `port` because the SRV record already carries the port. The code includes comments acknowledging the SRV record is authoritative, treating TXT `port` as redundant.\n**Status:** Deviation (minor -- the redundant field does not cause harm, but deviates from the contract)\n\n---\n\n### [MAJOR] Unknown TXT Version Handling Does Not Match Spec\n**Spec reference:** Plan, Discovery Contract (\"Unknown version handling: log warning, skip peer, no crash\"); Chunk 1 item 5\n**Finding:** When `decode_txt()` encounters `v=2`, it returns `Err(TxtError::InvalidVersion(\"2\"))`. This does not crash, which is correct. However, the spec says to \"log a warning\" -- the current implementation delegates logging to callers (since `decode_txt` is a pure function). More importantly, the version check `if version != 1` treats any non-1 version as invalid. The function signature `Result<(RoutingKey, u16, u8), TxtError>` means callers can pattern-match on the error and skip the peer gracefully.\n\nThe behavior is functionally correct (skip peer, no crash), but the \"log warning\" part is caller responsibility. There is no test specifically verifying that `v=2` results in `InvalidVersion` (the existing `invalid_version` test uses `\"not_a_number\"`, and `version_256_overflows_u8` tests overflow, but `v=2` as a valid-but-unsupported version is not explicitly tested).\n**Status:** Partial -- functionally safe but missing an explicit `v=2` test case\n\n---\n\n### [INFO] Fake Backend for Deterministic Tests\n**Spec reference:** Plan, Chunk 1 item 6\n**Finding:** `FakeDiscoveryBackend` in `fake.rs` supports `inject_peer()`, `inject_updated()`, `inject_lost()`, implements `DiscoveryBackend`, and is gated behind `#[cfg(any(test, feature = \"test-utils\"))]`. The `test-utils` feature enables external crates to use it. Well-tested with 6 unit tests covering inject/receive, advertising state machine, multiple subscribers, and shutdown.\n**Status:** Compliant\n\n---\n\n### [INFO] mdns-sd as Optional Feature-Gated Backend\n**Spec reference:** Plan, Chunk 1 item 7\n**Finding:** The `mdns-sd` feature in `Cargo.toml` gates `dep:mdns-sd` and `dep:hostname`. The `MdnsSdBackend` module is conditionally compiled with `#[cfg(feature = \"mdns-sd\")]`. The backend uses `mdns_sd::ServiceDaemon` and correctly maps between `mdns_sd::ServiceEvent` variants and `DiscoveryEvent`.\n**Status:** Compliant\n\n---\n\n### [MINOR] bind_interfaces Not Supported\n**Spec reference:** Plan, Chunk 1 item 7 (\"DiscoveryBackend must accept interface filter from config (bind_interfaces)\")\n**Finding:** `MdnsSdBackend::new()` takes no parameters. There is no `bind_interfaces` configuration passed to the constructor or to `mdns_sd::ServiceDaemon`. The `mdns-sd` crate does support interface binding via `ServiceDaemon::new_with_if_addrs()` or similar API, but this is not wired up. The plan explicitly requires `bind_interfaces` support in Chunk 1.\n**Status:** Deviation\n\n---\n\n### [INFO] Service Type Matches Whitepaper\n**Spec reference:** WHITEPAPER.md Section 11.2, 11.6; ROADMAP.md v0.4\n**Finding:** `DEFAULT_SERVICE_TYPE` is `\"_reme._tcp.local.\"` which matches the whitepaper's `_reme._tcp.local` service type. The trailing dot is correct DNS-SD convention.\n**Status:** Compliant\n\n---\n\n### [MINOR] DiscoveryService Type Not Present\n**Spec reference:** Plan, \"Public Interfaces and Config Changes\" bullet (\"DiscoveryService\")\n**Finding:** The