.rs`, lines 199-205\n\n**Current:**\n```rust\npub fn replace_http_target(&self, old_id: &TargetId, new_target: HttpTarget) -> bool {\n    if let Some(ref pool) = self.http_pool {\n        pool.replace_target(old_id, new_target)\n    } else {\n        false\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Suggestion:** Use `.is_some_and()` like `remove_http_target` does, or use the `map(...).unwrap_or(false)` pattern:\n```rust\npub fn replace_http_target(&self, old_id: &TargetId, new_target: HttpTarget) -> bool {\n    self.http_pool\n        .as_ref()\n        .map(|pool| pool.replace_target(old_id, new_target))\n        .unwrap_or(false)\n}\n```\n\n**Why:** The three coordinator mutation methods use three different delegation styles: `if let` with no return (`add_http_target`), `.is_some_and()` (`remove_http_target`), and `if let` with else (`replace_http_target`). Unifying to `.map().unwrap_or(false)` for the two that return `bool` improves consistency. Note: `.is_some_and()` cannot be used here because the closure needs to consume `new_target`, but `.map()` works.\n\n---\n\n### Finding 3: `quorum_target_count` can be expressed via `quorum_target_ids`\n\n**File:** `/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/crates/reme-transport/src/coordinator.rs`, lines 773-794\n\n**Current:** `quorum_target_count` and `quorum_target_ids` duplicate the same pool-iteration and filtering logic. The only difference is that one counts and the other collects IDs.\n\n**Suggestion:**\n```rust\n#[allow(clippy::cast_possible_truncation)]\npub fn quorum_target_count(&self, config: &TieredDeliveryConfig) -> u32 {\n    self.quorum_target_ids(config).len() as u32\n}\n```\n\n**Why:** Eliminates ~20 lines of duplicated filtering logic. The performance cost of collecting IDs only to count them is negligible -- these are small vectors (a handful of transport targets). If performance ever matters here, the right fix would be a shared helper that takes a generic collector, not maintaining two parallel implementations.\n\n---\n\n### Finding 