here since we're in a std::thread context\n// or use tokio::task::spawn_blocking if called from async context\nmatch status_rx.recv() {\n    Ok(mdns_sd::UnregisterStatus::OK) => {}\n    Ok(mdns_sd::UnregisterStatus::NotFound) => {\n        warn!(\"mDNS-SD: unregister reported service not found\");\n    }\n    Err(e) => return Err(DiscoveryError::BackendError(e.to_string())),\n}\n```\n\nFor `shutdown()`, similarly receive from the `DaemonStatus` channel, or at minimum note in doc comments that shutdown is fire-and-forget. Given `shutdown()` is async, `tokio::task::spawn_blocking` is the right wrapper.\n\n---\n\n### [CRITICAL] `std::thread::spawn` bridge thread leaks on `shutdown()` — no cancellation mechanism\n\n**File:** `/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/crates/reme-discovery/src/mdns_sd.rs:94-123`\n\n**Description:** The browse thread spawned by `ensure_browsing()` exits only when `browse_receiver.recv()` returns `Err`, which happens when the sender side is dropped. However, `shutdown()` calls `self.daemon.shutdown()` but does not join or signal the browse thread. The thread will block on `browse_receiver.recv()` until the daemon closes the channel. There is no join handle stored to confirm the thread has exited before `shutdown()` returns `Ok(())`. In practice this is a latent resource leak in test scenarios where many backends are created and destroyed, and in production it means `shutdown()` returning does not guarantee network resources are released.\n\nAdditionally, `state.browsing` is never reset to `false` after thread exit or shutdown, so `ensure_browsing()` cannot be called again if the backend is somehow reused after a partial failure.\n\n**Suggestion:** Store the `JoinHandle<()>` in `MdnsState` and join it in `shutdown()`:\n\n```rust\nstruct MdnsState {\n    advertising: bool,\n    registered_fullname: Option<String>,\n    browse_handle: Option<std::thread::JoinHandle<()>>,\n}\n```\n\nThen in `shutdown()`:\n```rust\nlet handle = state.browse_handle.take();\n// ... shutdown daemon ...\nif let Some(h) = handle {\n    let _ = h.join(); // wait for thread to drain and exit\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## Major\n\n### [MAJOR] TOCTOU race in `start_advertising()` — double-registration is possible under concurrent calls\n\n**File:** `/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/crates/reme-discovery/src/mdns_sd.rs:129-178`\n\n**Description:** The lock is intentionally dropped between the \"check advertising flag\" step (Phase 1) and the \"register with daemon + commit state\" step (Phase 3). A comment says \"no lock held\" during Phase 2. If `start_advertising()` is called concurrently from two tasks (which is valid since `DiscoveryBackend` is `Send + Sync` and `async`), both callers can pass the Phase 1 check and proceed to register with the daemon simultaneously. The result is two services registered under different fullnames, but only the last one committed to `registered_fullname`. The first registration is then permanently orphaned — it will never be unregistered.\n\n**Suggestion:** Either hold the lock through the entire operation (acceptable since `MdnsState` is a `Mutex`, not an async lock — the critical section is very short), or use a `tokio::sync::Mutex` and hold it across the async boundary. Given this is async code, `tokio::sync::Mutex` is more appropriate here anyway:\n\n```rust\n// In MdnsSdBackend, replace std::sync::Mutex with tokio::sync::Mutex<MdnsState>\n// Then: let mut state = self.state.lock().await;\n// Hold the guard across the entire start_advertising body\n```\n\nAlternatively, keep `std::sync::Mutex` but use an atomic `advertising` flag separate from the rest of state to provide a fast-path check-and-set with `AtomicBool::compare_exchange`.\n\n---\n\n### [MAJOR] `ensure_browsing()` is called from `subscribe()` which is `&self` and sync — but holding `std::sync::Mutex` inside async context\n\n**File:** `/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/crates/reme-discovery/src/mdns_sd.rs:76-124`\n\n**Description:** `ensure_browsing()` takes `&self` and acquires `self.state.lock().unwrap()`. It is called from `subscribe()`, which itself is a sync method but will be called from async contexts. The lock is held while calling `self.daemon.browse()` — an external call whose latency is unknown and which could potentially block if the daemon's command channel is full. Holding a `std::sync::Mutex` across a potentially-blocking call inside an async task starves the Tokio executor on that thread.\n\n**Suggestion:** Keep the `std::sync::Mutex` but narrow its scope to only protecting the `browsing` flag — drop the lock before calling `self.daemon.browse()`. If concurrent calls to `subscribe()` race, the second browse call can be ignored after the fact. Alternatively, split `ensure_browsing` into a separate `async fn` using a `tokio::sync::Mutex` or `tokio::sync::OnceCell`.\n\n---\n\n### [MAJOR] Version check in `decode_txt()` is hard-coded to reject version != 1 — no forward compatibility\n\n**File:** `/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/crates/reme-discovery/src/txt.rs:69-71`\n\n**Description:**\n```rust\nif version != 1 {\n    return Err(TxtError::InvalidVersion(v_str.clone()));\n}\n```\n\nThe `encode_txt` function accepts any `version: u8`, yet the decoder unconditionally rejects anything that is not exactly `1`. This means a future minor protocol bump would cause all existing nodes to permanently discard peers running the new version, triggering a hard flag day. The issue is that `TxtError::InvalidVersion` is indistinguishable (at the type level) from a malformed version field.\n\n**Suggestion:** Add a dedicated error variant for unsupported-but-valid versions:\n\n```rust\n#[error(\"unsupported version: {0}, expected 1\")]\nUnsupportedVersion(u8),\n```\n\nThis lets callers distinguish \"garbage data\" from \"newer peer I can't talk to\" and log/handle them differently. Also consider whether the version field should be a range check (`version >= 1`) rather than exact equality, depending on the intended compatibility policy.\n\n---\n\n### [MAJOR] `encode_txt` accepts `version: u8` but decoder only accepts `1` — caller can encode invalid TXT records\n\n**File:** `/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/crates/reme-discovery/src/txt.rs:44`\n\n**Description:** The public signature `encode_txt(routing_key: &RoutingKey, port: u16, version: u8)` allows callers to pass any version byte. A call with `version: 0` or `version: 2` produces a TXT map that `decode_txt` will always reject. The function silently accepts invalid input.\n\n**Suggestion:** Either remove the `version` parameter and hard-code `1` in `encode_txt` (if versioning is internal), or validate the input:\n\n```rust\npub fn encode_txt(routing_key: &RoutingKey, port: u16) -> HashMap<String, String> {\n    // version is always 1 for this protocol revision\n    ...\n    (TXT_KEY_VERSION.to_owned(), \"1\".to_owned()),\n    ...\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## Minor\n\n### [MINOR] `FakeDiscoveryBackend` broadcast channel capacity (64) differs from `MdnsSdBackend` (128)\n\n**File:** `/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/crates/reme-discovery/src/fake.rs:21` vs `/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/crates/reme-discovery/src/mdns_sd.rs:39`\n\n**Description:** The fake backend uses `broadcast::channel(64)`, the real backend uses `broadcast::channel(128)`. Tests that measure backpressure or lag behavior against the fake will observe different semantics than production. In a slow-consumer scenario, a test will start dropping messages at half the capacity of the real backend.\n\n**Suggestion:** Define a shared constant in `types.rs` or `lib.rs`:\n```rust\npub(crate) const DISCOVERY_CHANNEL_CAPACITY: usize = 128;\n```\nAnd use it in both backends.\n\n---\n\n### [MINOR] `#[tokio::test] async fn` tests in `fake.rs` contain no `.await` — misleading test structure\n\n**File:** `/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/crates/reme-discovery/src/fake.rs:99-113`, `115-127`, `129-141`, `173-183`, `185-198`\n\n**Description:** Five of the six test functions are declared `async fn` decorated with `#[tokio::test]` but contain no `.await` expressions (except `advertising_state_machine` which does call `await` on the async trait methods). The non-awaiting tests use `try_recv()` which is synchronous. `#[tokio::test]` adds runtime overhead and communicates intent (\"this test exercises async behavior\") that doesn't hold.\n\nThe `advertising_state_machine` test correctly uses `async` + `await`. The inject/receive tests do not need the runtime.\n\n**Suggestion:** Change the inject/receive tests to plain `#[test] fn`. This is a clarity and compile-time cost issue, not a correctness issue — the tests pass either way.\n\n---\n\n### [MINOR] `RawDiscoveredPeer::discovered_at` uses `std::time::Instant` — not serializable or comparable across processes\n\n**File:** `/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/crates/reme-discovery/src/types.rs:19`\n\n**Description:** `Instant` is not `PartialOrd`-comparable between values from different processes and has no stable serialization. If `RawDiscoveredPeer` is ever stored, logged as structured data, or compared across a serialization boundary, `Instant` will be problematic. This is a design-time decision worth flagging while the API is new.\n\n**Suggestion:** This is acceptable for an in-process, ephemeral discovery cache. Document explicitly that `discovered_at` is a monotonic local timestamp for cache expiry purposes only, and cannot be compared across process boundaries. If persistence is anticipated, switch to `std::time::SystemTime` or a `u64` epoch millis.\n\n---\n\n### [MINOR] `val_str()` on key-only TXT properties returns `\"\"` — silently overwrites with empty string\n\n**File:** `/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/crates/reme-discovery/src/mdns_sd.rs:63`\n\n**Description:** `prop.val_str()` returns `\"\"` for key-only TXT entries (where `val()` is `None`). The code maps all TXT properties into `HashMap<String, String>` unconditionally. Key-only entries become `(\"key\", \"\")` which is indistinguishable at the decode layer from an explicitly