          "text": "<task-notification>\n<task-id>aaeb********e5e6</task-id>\n<tool-use-id>tool********h79R</tool-use-id>\n<output-file>/tmp/claude-1000/-home-leon0399-Projects-reme/36b495c0-95b9-49fc-8523-b911e74011a9/tasks/aaeb9183fb7abe5e6.output</output-file>\n<status>completed</status>\n<summary>Agent \"Spec review: discovery controller\" completed</summary>\n<result>Now I have all the information needed. Here is the full spec review.\n\n---\n\n## Discovery Controller Spec Review\n\n### [MAJOR] Missing `verified_peer_index: HashMap<PublicID, Vec<TargetId>>`\n**Spec reference:** Plan, Chunk 3 -- \"Maintain `verified_peer_index: HashMap<PublicID, Vec<TargetId>>`\"\n**Finding:** The controller uses `peer_index: HashMap<String, PeerEntry>` keyed by mDNS instance name. There is no secondary index mapping `PublicID -> Vec<TargetId>`. The plan explicitly requires this for two edge cases: (EDGE-1) atomic IP change handling via remove-old+insert-new on the same PublicID, and (EDGE-4) multi-device support where the same PublicID appears on multiple physical devices with distinct instance names. Without this index, there is no efficient way to find all targets belonging to a given identity, and multi-device target racing (Direct tier races all targets for a PublicID) cannot be implemented correctly at the coordinator level.\n**Status:** Deviation\n\n### [MAJOR] No periodic refresh of verified peers\n**Spec reference:** Plan, Chunk 3 -- \"refreshes verified direct peers periodically and on transport failure\"; WHITEPAPER 11.6 -- \"Periodic identity refresh (5 min default) detects DHCP reassignment\"; ROADMAP v0.4 -- \"Background identity refresh task\"\n**Finding:** The controller event loop only reacts to `DiscoveryEvent` variants (`PeerDiscovered`, `PeerUpdated`, `PeerLost`). There is no timer, no `tokio::time::interval`, and no mechanism to proactively re-verify peers on a schedule. The `refresh_interval_secs` config field specified in the plan does not exist in the config struct. Without periodic refresh, a DHCP reassignment that does not trigger an mDNS update will leave a stale target in the coordinator indefinitely, potentially routing messages to the wrong device.\n**Status:** Deviation\n\n### [MAJOR] No stale-peer lifecycle (Suspended state, circuit breaker, stale_timeout)\n**Spec reference:** Plan, Stale-Peer Lifecycle -- \"Mark target as Suspended\"; \"Circuit breaker (2 failures for Ephemeral)\"; \"stale_timeout (60s) proactive re-verification\"\n**Finding:** None of the three stale-peer mechanisms exist. There is no `Suspended` state, no failure counter, no `stale_timeout`. Peers go directly from verified to removed only via `PeerLost` mDNS events. If a peer becomes unreachable without sending an mDNS goodbye (e.g., abrupt power loss), its target remains registered and the coordinator will keep attempting delivery with no circuit breaker.\n**Status:** Deviation\n\n### [MAJOR] No channel binding in identity verification (SEC-3)\n**Spec reference:** Plan, Identity Verification Flow -- \"Channel binding (SEC-3 mitigation): The signed data becomes: `reme-identity-v1:` || challenge || responder_ip:port || node_pubkey\"\n**Finding:** `build_identity_sign_data()` in `crates/reme-encryption/src/lib.rs:376` signs only `\"reme-identity-v1:\" || challenge || node_pubkey` (81 bytes). The responder IP:port is not included. The controller's `verify_peer_identity()` does not pass the address to the sign-data builder. This leaves the MITM relay attack vector open: an attacker can forward the challenge to the real peer, receive a valid signature, and relay it back to the verifier. The plan explicitly created Chunk 5 for this, noting it \"can overlap with Chunk 4\", so this is an expected deferral, but the code has no TODO or tracking reference.\n**Status:** Deviation (expected -- Chunk 5 not yet implemented, but no tracking comment in the verification code)\n\n### [MINOR] Timing safety: short-circuits on first candidate match (SEC-2)\n**Spec reference:** Plan, Identity Verification Flow -- \"always iterate all N and use constant-time comparison for the final pass/fail decision. Do not short-circuit on first match.\"\n**Finding:** In `verify_peer_identity()` at line 364, the loop over candidates breaks on the first successful `verify_xeddsa()` call (line 365 returns `Ok(Some(...))`). The plan says to iterate all N candidates and use a constant-time final decision to prevent timing side-channel leakage of which candidate index matched. The current implementation leaks timing information proportional to the position of the matching candidate in the list.\n**Status:** Deviation\n\n### [MINOR] Config field name mismatch: `auto_direct_known_contacts` vs `allow_direct_lan`\n**Spec reference:** Plan, Public Interfaces and Config Changes -- `lan_discovery.auto_direct_known_contacts` default `true`\n**Finding:** The plan specifies `auto_direct_known_contacts`. The implementation uses `allow_direct_lan`. The semantic meaning is similar but the names differ. Additionally, the plan specifies `refresh_interval_secs` (default 300) which is completely absent from the config struct.\n**Status:** Partial (field exists with different name; `refresh_interval_secs` missing entirely)\n\n### [COMPLIANT] Subscribes to DiscoveryEvent stream\n**Spec reference:** Plan, Chunk 3\n**Finding:** The `spawn()` function takes a `broadcast::Receiver<DiscoveryEvent>` and loops on `events.recv()`, handling `PeerDiscovered`, `PeerUpdated`, and `PeerLost`. Handles `Lagged` and `Closed` errors.\n**Status:** Compliant\n\n### [COMPLIANT] Matches candidates against known contacts using advertised rk\n**Spec reference:** Plan, Chunk 3\n**Finding:** `contact_index: HashMap<[u8; 16], Vec<PublicID>>` is built from contacts at construction. `handle_discovered()` decodes TXT records to extract `routing_key`, then looks up candidates via `self.contact_index.get(&routing_key)`.\n**Status:** Compliant\n\n### [COMPLIANT] Skips HTTP probe when rk matches zero contacts\n**Spec reference:** Plan, Identity Verification Flow\n**Finding:** Line 128: `let Some(candidates) = self.contact_index.get(&routing_key) else { return; }`. When routing key is not in the contact index, the function returns without making any HTTP request.\n**Status:** Compliant\n\n### [COMPLIANT] Adds/removes send-only direct targets via coordinator\n**Spec reference:** Plan, Chunk 3\n**Finding:** `handle_new()` calls `coordinator.add_http_target()`, `handle_lost()` calls `coordinator.remove_http_target()`, and `handle_update()` calls `coordinator.replace_http_target()`. Targets are created via `HttpTargetConfig::ephemeral()` which defaults to SEND-only capabilities.\n**Status:** Compliant\n\n### [COMPLIANT] Resource limits: max 256 tracked discovered peers\n**Spec reference:** Plan, Chunk 3\n**Finding:** `max_peers` field with default 256 (from `DEFAULT_LAN_MAX_PEERS`). Enforced at line 138: `if !is_update && self.peer_index.len() >= self.max_peers`. The `max(1)` clamp at line 94 prevents a zero-peer misconfiguration.\n**Status:** Compliant\n\n### [COMPLIANT] `lan_discovery.enabled` default false\n**Spec reference:** Plan, Public Interfaces and Config Changes\n**Finding:** `LanDiscoveryConfig::default()` sets `enabled: false`. Tested in `test_lan_discovery_config_default()`.\n**Status:** Compliant\n\n### [COMPLIANT] IP change handling via atomic replace\n**Spec reference:** Plan, EDGE-1\n**Finding:** `handle_update()` uses `coordinator.replace_http_target(&old_target_id, target)` which atomically removes the old target and inserts the new one. This is correct for single-instance IP changes. However, without the `verified_peer_index`, cross-instance IP changes for the same PublicID are not tracked (see first finding).\n**Status:** Partial (single-instance case works; cross-instance case not addressed)\n\n### [COMPLIANT] WHITEPAPER challenge-response protocol basics\n**Spec reference:** WHITEPAPER 11.6\n**Finding:** Challenge is 32 random bytes (`r