x exists to handle exactly that case.\n\n**Suggestion:** Always iterate all candidates, then return the first match found:\n```rust\nlet mut matched: Option<PublicID> = None;\nfor candidate in candidates {\n    let sign_data = build_identity_sign_data(&challenge, &candidate.to_bytes());\n    if candidate.verify_xeddsa(&sign_data, &signature) && matched.is_none() {\n        matched = Some(*candidate);\n        // do NOT break — continue iterating all N\n    }\n}\nOk(matched)\n```\nNote that `verify_xeddsa` itself must also not leak timing, which depends on the `xed25519` crate internals — worth verifying that `xed25519::PublicKey::verify` is constant-time.\n\n**Confidence: 90** — Directly contradicts the SEC-2 requirement stated in the plan.\n\n---\n\n### [CRITICAL] Identity challenge does not bind to the responder's IP:port (SEC-3 missing)\n\n**File:** `/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/apps/client/src/discovery/controller.rs:324–369`\n\n**Description:** `build_identity_sign_data` produces `\"reme-identity-v1:\" || challenge || node_pubkey`. The responder's IP:port is not included in the signed data. A MITM on the LAN can intercept the challenge, forward it to the real peer, receive the valid signature, and relay it back — the verifier has no way to distinguish this from a direct response.\n\nThe plan explicitly mandates Chunk 5 (channel binding): \"The challenge must include binding material to prevent MITM relay attacks. The signed data becomes: `\"reme-identity-v1:\" || challenge || responder_ip:port || node_pubkey`.\"\n\nThis is acknowledged as a deferred chunk (\"Chunk 5: can overlap with Chunk 4\") not yet implemented, but it represents a fundamental gap in the security model as shipped. The controller currently constructs URLs like `format!(\"http://{}\", SocketAddr::new(addr, peer.port))` — the `addr` and `peer.port` are already available at call time and could be threaded into `verify_peer_identity`.\n\n**Suggestion:** Either: (a) block merging until Chunk 5 is 