fragility rather than a current breakage.\n\n---\n\n### [MAJOR] URL-unchanged short-circuit skips re-verification when identity may have changed\n\n**File:** `/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/apps/client/src/discovery/controller.rs:157–169`\n\n**Description:** On a `PeerUpdated` event, if the current URL still appears in the updated peer's address list, verification is skipped entirely:\n\n```rust\nif stored_url_still_valid {\n    debug!(\"Update with matching address, skipping re-verification\");\n    return;\n}\n```\n\nThis is a security trade-off: it avoids redundant verification for benign address-unchanged updates, but it means a peer whose cryptographic identity has changed (key rotation, compromise) will retain its registered target as long as its IP doesn't move. The plan notes \"verified peers are refreshed periodically\" but that refresh mechanism is not implemented in this controller — there is no `refresh_interval_secs` timer, no stale-timeout, and no circuit-breaker hook. The short-circuit is therefore permanent for stationary peers, not temporary between periodic re-checks.\n\nThe plan states: \"On verification failure, mark target `Suspended` before removal. Circuit breaker provides fast path (2 failures for Ephemeral). `stale_timeout` (60s) triggers proactive re-verification.\" None of this exists yet, so the short-circuit has no safety net.\n\n**Suggestion:** Either: (a) document clearly that the short-circuit is intentional and that periodic re-verification (deferred) is the safety net — with a `FIXME` noting the missing refresh mechanism — or (b) remove the short-circuit for now since the refresh loop doesn't exist yet. A silent skip is harder to audit than an explicit TODO.\n\n**Confidence: 80** — The short-circuit is architecturally incomplete given the missing refresh mechanism.\n\n---\n\n### [MAJOR] `max_peers` clamped to minimum 1 silently, with no user warning\n\n**File:** `/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/apps/client/src/discovery/controller.rs:94`