om `spawn()`, and have the caller handle it gracefully (log warning, continue without LAN discovery). Alternatively, construct the `reqwest::Client` outside `spawn()` and inject it, so a construction failure can be reported to the caller.\n\n**Confidence: 80** — Applies directly to the AGENTS.md no-new-unwrap principle and can cause a silent task crash.\n\n---\n\n### [MINOR] `contact_index` collision handling is correct but not tested for the realistic case\n\n**File:** `/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/apps/client/src/discovery/controller.rs:406–419`\n\n**Description:** The `controller_contact_index_groups_by_routing_key` test artificially assigns the same routing key `[0xAA; 16]` to two identities, which will never collide in practice. The real routing key collision scenario — two different `PublicID` values whose `BLAKE3(PublicID)[0..16]` prefix collides — is not tested. That said, the grouping logic itself is correct.\n\nAdditionally, the test at line 400 passes `max_peers: 256` but the struct field is only readable in tests via direct field access because `peer_index` and `contact_index` are private. This is fine — it tests the public interface correctly.\n\n**Suggestion:** Add a test that verifies both candidates are tried during verification (i.e., the second candidate succeeds when the first doesn't), exercising the iteration-to-completion behavior rather than just the indexing.\n\n**Confidence: 75** — Not a bug, but important test coverage gap for the security-sensitive path.\n\n---\n\n### [MINOR] Shutdown cleanup loop iterates then clears — unnecessary double work\n\n**File:** `/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/apps/client/src/discovery/controller.rs:82–86`\n\n**Description:**\n```rust\nfor (name, entry) in &controller.peer_index {\n    coordinator.remove_http_target(&entry.target_id);\n    debug!(instance = %name, \"Deregistered peer on shutdown\");\n}\ncontroller.peer_index.clear();\n```\n\n`peer_index.clear()` after the loop is correct but unnecessary since the 