ile:** `/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/apps/client/src/tui/app.rs:330, 936–942`\n\n**Description:** `CoordinatorHandle`'s `Drop` implementation calls `cancel_token.cancel()`, stopping all HTTP polling receiver tasks. The field `_coordinator_handle` is dropped when `App` is dropped — which happens *after* `run()` returns. However, within `run()`, the shutdown sequence is:\n\n```\nshutdown_discovery().await   // cancels + awaits discovery task, then shuts down mDNS\nshutdown_embedded_node().await\nreturn Ok(())                // App dropped here → _coordinator_handle dropped → polling cancelled\n```\n\nThe coordinator polling is cancelled at `App` drop, which is after all async shutdown work finishes. That ordering is correct *in isolation*. However, any messages that arrive in the HTTP polling task's final tick after `running = false` is set but before `App` drops will be received, forwarded on the unbounded channel, and never consumed (the main loop has exited). These messages accumulate in `coordinator_events` until the channel is dropped. This is a benign memory leak bounded by the time between loop exit and `App` drop, but it could be a source of confusion.\n\nMore substantively: if `shutdown_discovery` takes a long time (e.g. mDNS backend hangs on `shutdown()`), the coordinator polling tasks remain active and accumulate messages the entire time. This is not harmful but is wasteful.\n\n**Confidence: 80**\n\n**Suggestion:** Cancel `_coordinator_handle` explicitly at the top of the shutdown sequence before `shutdown_discovery`. Replace `_coordinator_handle: CoordinatorHandle` with a method call:\n\n```rust\nself._coordinator_handle.stop(); // explicit before discovery/node shutdown\nself.shutdown_discovery().await;\nself.shutdown_embedded_node().await;\n```\n\nThe `CoordinatorHandle::stop()` method already exists.\n\n---\n\n### [MAJOR] `backend.subscribe()` is called before `Arc::new(backend)` — the `Arc` doesn't wrap the browsing backend that was subscribed to\n\n**File:** `/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/apps/client/src/tui/app.rs:709, 743`\n\n**Description:** At line 709, `backend.subscribe()` is called on the owned `backend`. This triggers `ensure_browsing()` which starts an `std::thread` that holds a clone of `backend.tx` (broadcast sender). At line 743, `Arc::new(backend)` wraps the same `backend` instance. This is fine — the browse thread captures `tx: broadcast::Sender`, not the `MdnsSdBackend` itself, so the Mutex state and daemon are correctly owned by the single `Arc`. There is no correctness issue here.\n\n**Correction — confidence does not reach threshold. Withdrawing this as a finding.**\n\n---\n\n### [MINOR] Port extraction with `rsplit(':').next()` silently falls back to 23004 on parse failure\n\n**File:** `/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/apps/client/src/tui/app.rs:724–728`\n\n**Description:** The address formats `rsplit` handles are correct — `\"0.0.0.0:23004\"`, `\"[::]:23004\"`, `\"[::1]:23004\"` all yield `\"23004\"` as the last colon-split segment. However, if `http_bind` contains a non-numeric port (e.g., a misconfiguration like `\"0.0.0.0:badport\"`), `p.parse().ok()` silently returns `None` and the code falls back to port `23004`. The HTTP server was already bound (at line 511) to the actual configured address, so mDNS will advertise port 23004 while the server is actually bound to a different port. Other nodes will try to contact the wrong port.\n\n**Confidence: 82**\n\n**Suggestion:** Log a warning when the fallback fires, or better, extract the port by binding the `TcpListener` and calling `listener.local_addr()` to get the actual bound port — this is already available after `http_server::bind_server()` (line 511). The listener is moved into `tokio::spawn` at line 521 but `local_addr()` can be called before that. This would be both accurate and handle port 0 (OS-assigned port) correctly.\n\n---\n\n### [MINOR] Discovery controller task `JoinHandle` is `Option` but never awaited when `allow_direct_lan = false`\n\n**File:** `/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/apps/client/src/tui/app.rs:719, 744`\n\n**Description:** When `allow_direct_lan = false`, `controller_handle` is `None`. The tuple returned is `(Some(backend), Some(cancel), None)`. In `shutdown_discovery`, the `discovery_task.take()` branch is skipped. `discovery_cancel` is set to `Some(cancel)` — so `cancel.cancel()` is called on a `CancellationToken` that no task is listening to. This is harmless but wastes a token allocation. More importantly it means `discovery_cancel` being `Some` while `discovery_task` is `None` is a valid state the struct must silently tolerate.\n\n**Confidence: 80**\n\n**Suggestion:** When `allow_direct_lan = false`, don't create or store the `CancellationToken` either. Set all three to `None`:\n\n```rust\n(Some(backend), None, None)\n```\n\nThe mDNS backend doesn't use the `CancellationToken`, only the controller task does.\n\n---\n\n### [MINOR] `unwrap_or_else` on `storage.list_contacts()` silently degrades to empty contact list\n\n**File:** `/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/apps/client/src/tui/app.rs:696–701`\n\n**Description:** If `list_contacts()` fails (e.g., SQLite corruption), the discovery controller silently starts with zero contacts. All discovered peers will be treated as strangers and none will be verified. The `warn!` log is appropriate, but the behavior is invisible to the user — the app continues and LAN discovery appears to \"work\" but never registers any peers. Per the AGENTS.md checklist, this is categorized as the `unwrap_or_else` used in an application binary context, not a library crate, so the usage is acceptable by project rules. The degraded state could be better surfaced.\n\n**Confidence: 80**\n\n**Suggestion:** This is appropriate for an application-level fallback. The existing `warn!` log is the right approach. Consider adding a status bar notification like `\"LAN discovery: contacts unavailable, peer matching disabled\"` so the user sees the degraded state.\n\n---\n\n### [NIT] `DiscoveryBackend` import is unused when `lan_discovery.enabled = false`\n\n**File:** `/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/apps/client/src/tui/app.rs:14`\n\n**Description:** `use reme_discovery::DiscoveryBackend` is imported unconditionally. It's needed for the `.subscribe()`, `.start_advertising()`, and `.shutdown()` trait method calls inside the `if config.lan_discovery.enabled` block. Rust resolves trait method calls without needing the trait in scope for the call site (for inherent methods), but the `DiscoveryBackend` trait is needed because `subscribe()` and `start_advertising()` are trait methods. The import is correct and necessary if LAN discovery is enabled at runtime. This is fine.\n\n**Correction — not actually an issue. Withdrawing.**\n\n---\n\n## Summary\n\n**Critical:** None.\n\n**Major (2 real issues):**\n\n1. **Static contact snapshot** — contacts added at runtime are invisible to the discovery controller. Every user who adds a new contact while the app is running and then attempts LAN delivery will silently fail until restart.\n2. **Coordinator polling cancellation ordering** — `_coordinator_handle` drops after async shutdown work completes, meaning coordinator polling accumulates unread events during shutdown. Explicit cancellation before `shutdown_discovery()` is cleaner.\n\n**Minor (2 issues):**\n\n3. **Port extraction silent fallback** — `rsplit(':').next().and_then(|p| p.parse().ok()).unwrap_or(23004)` silently advertises the wrong port on misconfiguration. Use the actual bound address from the listener.\n4. **Orphan `CancellationToken` when `allow_direct_lan = false`** — a cancel token is allocated and stored but no task uses it in this code path.\n\nThe migration from `CompositeTransport` to `TransportCoordinator` is complete and correct. `Arc<MdnsSdBackend>` lifetime management is sound. Shutdown ordering (discovery → embedded node) is correct. No Arc cycles. The `_coordinator_handle` drop semantic is correct but can be made explicit. The IP